VI, like you, started out with the Spring helper classes for Jasper Reports but quickly abandoned them as being too coarse-grained and inflexible, which is unusual for Spring
p169
aVIts like they were added as an afterthought
p170
aVThe big problem I had with them was that once they were compiled, it required an appserver bounce to put in new versions
p171
aVIn my case, I was after a solution whereby I could change them on disk and they'd recompile, much like how JSPs normally work (if you don't turn this feature off, which many production sites would)
p172
aVAlternatively, I wanted to be able to store the jrxml files in a database or run the reports remotely (eg through the JasperServer web services interface)
p173
aVThe Spring classes just made it all but impossible to implement such features
p174
aVSo my suggestion to you is: roll your own
p175
aVThere are a couple of gotchas along the way though, which I'll share with you to minimize the pain
p176
aVSome of these things aren't obvious from the documentation
p177
aVThe first thing you'll need is a jasper reports compiler
p178
aVThis is responsible for compiling a jrxml file into a JasperDesign object
p179
aVThere are several implemenations of this but the one you want is the JRJdtCompiler
p180
aVYou can instantiate and inject this in a Spring application context
p181
aVAvoid others like the beanshell compiler since running the report as a large beanshell script is not particularly fast or efficient (I found this out the hard way before I knew any better)
p182
aVYou will need to include the jar files for the JRJdtCompiler
p183
aVI think the full Jasper Reports dist includes this jar
p184
aVIts an eclipse product
p185
aVYou can store the JasperDesign anywhere you like (HttpSession, servlet context or whatever)
p186
aVThe fillReport() method is the primary one you're interested in
p187
aVIt creates a JasperPrint object, which is an instance of a run report
p188
aVParameters are just passed in as a Map
p189
aVNow to create a versino in HTML, PDF, etc, you need to export it
p190
aVYou use classes like the JRHtmlExporter and JRPdfExporter to do this
p191
aVThey require certain parameters
p192
aVThe tricky one is the HTML exporter because HTML obviously doesn't include the images
p193
aVJasper includes an ImageServlet class that fetches these from the session (where the JRHtmlExporter has put them) but you have to get the config of both the HTML exporter and image servlet just right and its hard to tell where you're going wrong
p194
aVI don't remember the specifics of it but theres an example of all this in the Jasper Reports Definitive Guide, which I'd highly recommend you get if you're spending anytime at all with this product
p195
aVIts fairly cheap at US$50
p196
aVYou could get the annual subscription too but in the 18+ months I've seen it I haven't seen a single change
p197
aVJust buy the new version when it comes out if you need it (which you probably won't)
