aVLet's consider the use cases:
p846
aVPackage private classes: use inner classes
p847
aVAnother poster suggested there is a (small) performance penalty for inner classes vs package private classes but, to me, that's not a good reason for bad design
p848
aVPackage private and inner classes I consider to be implementation details and, as such, I think it's better to "hide" them as inner classes;
p849
aVPackage private data members: I can see no reason for these at all; and
p850
aVPackage private methods: these are pretty much the equivalent of C++ friend methods
p851
aVC++ friends had one good raison d'etre and that was to externalize operator overloading outside of the class, which allowed the first argument to be something other than the class itself
p852
aVIn Java, there is no such use case, which just leaves doing an end-run around encapsulation and abstraction
p853
aVCompare this to protected methods, which are entirely justifiable when designing classes for extension
p854
aVI've seen cases where programmers inadvertently use protected methods in unrelated classes in the same package just because they come up on auto-completion lists
