p1117
aVI won't repeat the overview of the various technologies here
p1118
aVI've got a lot of experience in financial market information systems
p1119
aVA few of the things you said stuck out to me:
p1120
aVYou have a lot of raw data;
p1121
aVYou want to apply various aggregations to that data (eg open/high/low/close daily summaries);
p1122
aVHigh availability is probably an issue (it always is in these kinds of systems); and
p1123
aVLow latency is probably an issue (ditto)
p1124
aVNow for grid/cluster type solutions I divide them loosely into two categories:
p1125
aVMap-based solutions like Coherence or Terracotta; and
p1126
aVJavaspaces-based solutions like GigaSpaces
p1127
aVI've used Coherence a lot and the Map solution can be nice but it can be problematic too
p1128
aVCoherence maps can have listeners on them and you can use this sort of thing to do things like:
p1129
aVMarket price alerts (users may want a notification when a price reaches a certain level);
p1130
aVDerivative pricing (eg an exchange-traded option pricing system will want to reprice when an underlying security changes last traded price);
p1131
aVA trade-matching/booking system may want to match received trade notifications for reconciliation purposes;
p1132
aVetc
p1133
aVAll of these can be done with listeners but in Coherence for example listeners have to be cheap, which leads to things like a Map having a listener than writes something to another Map and this can chain on for awhile
p1134
aVAlso, modifying the cache entry can be problematic (although there are mechanisms for dealing with that kind of problem too; I'm talking about situations like turning off a market price alert so it doesn't trigger a second time)
p1135
aVI found GigaSpaces type grid solutions to be far more compelling for this kind of application
p1136
aVThe read (or destructive read) operation is a highly elegant and scalable solution and you can get transactional grid updates with sub-millisecond performance
p1137
aVConsider the two classic queueing architectures:
p1138
aVRequest/Response: a bad message can block the queue and while you can many senders and receivers (for scalability) scaling up the number of pipes isn't always straightforward; and
p1139
aVPublish/Subscribe: this decouples the sender and receiver but lacks scalability in that if you have multiple subscribers they'll each receive the message (not necessarily what you want with say a booking system)
p1140
aVIn GigaSpaces, a destructive read is like a scalable publish-subscribe system and a read operation is like the traditional publish-subscribe model
p1141
aVThere is a Map and JMS implementation built on top of the grid and it can do FIFO ordering
p1142
