VThe underlying protocol for database connections is typically TCP/IP based
p1524
aVThe connection can be terminated in one of several ways:
p1525
aVThe server closes it gracefully and receives an acknowledgement from the client;
p1526
aVThe client closes is gracefully and receives an acknowledgement from the server;
p1527
aVThe connection times out
p1528
aVThe client and server both separately are told by their respective operating systems that the connection has been closed;
p1529
aVThe connection is forcefully closed by either side
p1530
aVIn the case of (3), TCP connections must be kept alive by sending dummy messages every so often to avoid a timeout
p1531
aVYour connection may timeout because neither side is doing this (and for a database connection it's not something you typically want to do)
p1532
aVIt's entirely possible for a time for one side to think the connection is closed and hte other side to still believe it is open
p1533
aVMessages may get sent in those cases (and typically discarded)
p1534
aVEach connection ("socket") uses an operating system resource called a file descriptor (in UNIX parlance, your OS may call it something else), which is a handle to an I/O resource and the same thing used for an open file (again, OSs may vary)
p1535
aVThe limit on connections on your database will be the lowest of:
p1536
aVThe configured limit for the OS;
p1537
aVThe maximum file descriptors allowed for that process (minus any being used for I/O activity); and
p1538
aV(possibly) system settings or policies on connection limits
p1539
aVIf the connection isn't TCP based (eg a filesystem socket as is often used with MySQL on UNIX systems) the principles are in fact very simlar
p1540
aVAnyway, the moral of the story to take from this is that a database connection--regardless of its form--involves an operating system resource of some kind
p1541
aVYour program hsa directly or indirectly asked for that resource
p1542
aVIf the program dies, the operating system will reclaim it (perhaps not immediately but eventually)
p1543
aVIf the connection gets garbage collected then the resource will be released in much the same way as if it had been forcibly closed
p1544
aVIts that external resource (and not the code your client is using) that holds the connection open and drives any limits
