VIt depends in what context you mean but basically streaming data is analagous to asynchronous data
p2626
aVTake the Web as an example
p2627
aVThe Web (or HTTP specifically) is (basically) a request-response mechanism in that a client makes a request and receives a response (typically a Web page of some kind)
p2628
aVHTTP doesn't natively support the ability for servers to push content to clients
p2629
aVThere are a number of ways this can be faked, including:
p2630
aVPolling: forcing the client to make repeated requests, typically inconspicuously (as far as the client is concerned);
p2631
aVLong-lived connections: this is where the client makes a normal HTTP request but instead of returning immediately the server hangs on to the request until there's something to send back
p2632
aVWhen the request times out or a response is sent th eclient sends another request
p2633
aVIn this way you can fake server push;
p2634
aVPlug-ins: Java applets, Flash, Silverlight and others can be used to achieve this
p2635
aVAnything where the server effectively sends data to the client (rather than the client asking for it)--regardless of the mechanism and whether or not the client is polling for that data--can be characterised as streaming data
p2636
aVWith non-HTTP transports (eg vanilla TCP) server push is typically easier (but can still run afoul of firewalls and th elike)
p2637
aVAn example of this might be a sharetrading application that receives market information from a provider
p2638
aVThat's streaming data
