VIt's all about process and managing expectations and very little to do with the technical
p2648
aVThe mistake (imho) most clients make--particularly with smaller consultancies--is that they go for a fixed price contract (possibly with support being billed T&M;: time and materials)
p2649
aVThey do this as a risk management exercise so it's understandable
p2650
aVThe problem is that they are paying for that lower risk in three ways:
p2651
aVYou pay a premium for lower risk
p2652
aVThis is a fundamental principle that is as true in software development as it is in financial markets;
p2653
aVSo much risk can be put on the developer(s) that the cost goes up astronomically, which benefits precisely noone (well, it benefits the developer until things go catastrophically wrong, which they nearly always do eventually); and
p2654
aVYou spend so much time developing a specification and formalizing the deliverables and acceptance criteria that you forget in doing so you've just spent $300k writing a 300 page Word document instead of, you know, coding something
p2655
aVAll of this serves to make the end result more expensive for the client, demotivating for the developer (who wants to write 300 page Word docs
p2656
aVSeriously
p2657
aVand it delays the client actually getting anything (thus increasing the risk of scope creep, which is directly proportional to the length of the project)
