VSpeaking as someone who spent quite a bit of time working with JPA (Java Persistence API, basically the standardized ORM API for Java/J2EE/EJB), which includes Hibernate, EclipseLink, Toplink, OpenJPA and others, I'll share some of my observations
p2823
aVORMs are not fast
p2824
aVThey can be adequate and most of the time adequate is OK but in a high-volume low-latency environment they're a no-no;
p2825
aVIn general purpose programming languages like Java and C# you need an awful lot of magic to make them work (eg load-time weaving in Java, instrumentation, etc);
p2826
aVWhen using an ORM, rather than getting further from SQL (which seems to be the intent), you'll be amazed how much time you spend tweaking XML and/or annotations/attributes to get your ORM to generate performant SQL;
p2827
aVFor complex queries, there really is no substitute
p2828
aVLike in JPA there are some queries that simply aren't possible that are in raw SQL and when you have to use raw SQL in JPA it's not pretty (C#/
p2829
aVNet at least has dynamic types--var--which is a lot nicer than an Object array);
p2830
aVThere are an awful lot of "gotchas" when using ORMs
p2831
aVThis includes unintended or unexpected behavior, the fact that you have to build in the capability to do SQL updates to your database (by using refresh() in JPA or similar methods because JPA by default caches everything so it won't catch a direct database update--running direct SQL updates is a common production support activity);
p2832
aVThe object-relational mismatch is always going to cause problems
p2833
aVWith any such problem there is a tradeoff between complexity and completeness of the abstraction
p2834
aVAt times I felt JPA went too far and hit a real law of diminishing returns where the complexity hit wasn't justified by the abstraction
p2835
aVThere's another problem which takes a bit more explanation
p2836
aVThe traditional model for a Web application is to have a persistence layer and a presentation layer (possibly with a services or other layers in between but these are the important two for this discussion)
p2837
aVORMs force a rigid view from your persistence layer up to the presentation layer (ie your entities)
p2838
aVOne of the criticisms of more raw SQL methods is that you end up with all these VOs (value objects) or DTOs (data transfer objects) that are used by simply one query
p2839
aVThis is touted as an advantage of ORMs because you get rid of that
p2840
aVThing is those problems don't go away with ORMs, they simply move up to the presentation layer
p2841
aVInstead of creating VOs/DTOs for queries, you create custom presentation objects, typically one for every view
p2842
aVHow is this better
p2843
aVIMHO it isn't
p2844
aVI've written about this in ORM or SQL: Are we there yet
p2845
aVMy persistence technology of choice (in Java) these days is ibatis
p2846
aVIt's a pretty thin wrapper around SQL that does 90%+ of what JPA can do (it can even do lazy-loading of relationships although its not well-documented) but with far less overhead (in terms of complexity and actual code)
p2847
aVThis came up last year in a GWT application I was writing
p2848
aVLots of translation from EclipseLink to presentation objects in the service implementation
p2849
aVIf we were using ibatis it would've been far simpler to create the appropriate objects with ibatis and then pass them all the way up and down the stack
p2850
aVSome purists might argue this is Bad\u2122
p2851
aVMaybe so (in theory) but I tell you what: it would've led to simpler code, a simpler stack and more productivity
