aVThere's no reason that two entirely different processes can't talk to each other via it
p3862
aVLet me clarify
p3863
aVYou can run memcache on one or more servers
p3864
aVYou can configure your clients to speak to a specific set of instances
p3865
aVYou can run two (or more) different memcache processes on the same host (listening to different IP addresses and/or ports) and they're completely independent
p3866
aVIf your two applications talk to the same instance(s) then there's no reason they can't communicate
p3867
aVThe complication comes if you talk to multiple instances and partition your data (ie split it across different instances) then your clients need to know which instance to get the data from or put the data into
p3868
