aVI say that for a few reasons:
p3880
aVFirst, ORMs like NHibernate that really try and abstract away the database I think can be counterproductive, particularly when dealing with "legacy" databases
p3881
aVLegacy here doesn't mean what you think it means
p3882
aVTools like Hibernate and JPA (Java) define pretty much anything that doesn't do things the "proper" way as legacy, and that can include using composite keys (seriously, I read a JPA book taht called composite keys "legacy")
p3883
aVIbatis on the other hand gives you most of the power of an ORM (and some things that Hibernate, for example, can't do like the groupBy functionality) but still leaves you able to just write plain SQL
p3884
aVI imagine with a database that large you're going to have some questionable modelling decisions that will be difficult if not impossible to map into many ORMs
p3885
aVBy writing direct SQL you can cater for these situations in ibatis by definition
p3886
aVORMs that aren't vendor specific are also lowest common denominator when it comes to query language
p3887
aVIf all databases can't do it then you can't do it anywhere
p3888
aVOracle has one of the most sophisticated SQL dialects
p3889
aVYou should use it
p3890
aVThings like CONNECT PRIOR don't exist in many other SQL dialects (and thus aren't modelled in a performant manner in abstracted ORMs)
p3891
aVI wrote more about this in Using an ORM or plain SQL
p3892
aVThe fact that your hands are tied by existing design makes an even strong case for keeping as close to SQL as possible
