VCaching is just the practice of storing data in and retrieving data from a high-performance store (usually memory) either explicitly or implicitly
p3985
aVLet me explain
p3986
aVMemory is faster to access than a file, a remote URL (usually), a database or any other external store of information you like
p3987
aVSo if the act of using one of those external resources is significant then you may benefit from caching to increase performance
p3988
aVKnuth once said that premature optimization is the root of all evil
p3989
aVWell, premature caching is the root of all headaches as far as I'm concerned
p3990
aVDon't solve a problem until you have a problem
p3991
aVEvery decision you make comes at a cost that you'll pay to implement it now and pay again to change it later so the longer you can put off making a deicsion and changing your system the better
p3992
aVSo first identify that you actually have a problem and where it is
p3993
aVProfiling, logging and other forms of performance testing will help you here
p3994
aVI can't stress enough how important this step is
p3995
aVThe number of times I've seen people "optimize" something that isn't a problem is staggering
p3996
aVOk, so you have a performance problem
p3997
aVSay your pages are running a query that takes a long time
p3998
aVIf it's a read then you have a number of options:
p3999
aVRun the query as a separate process and put the result into a cache
p4000
aVAll pages simply access the cache
p4001
aVYou can update the cached version as often as is appropriate (once a day, once a week, one every 5 seconds, whatever is appropriate);
p4002
aVCache transparently through your persistence provider, ORM or whatever
p4003
aVOf course this depends on what technology you're using
p4004
aVHibernate and Ibatis for example support query result caching;
p4005
aVHave your pages run the query if the result isn't in the cache (or it's "stale", meaning it is calculated longer ago than the specified "age") and put it into the cache
p4006
aVThis has concurrency problems if two (or more) separate processes all decide they need to update the result so you end up running the same (expensive) query eight times at once
p4007
aVYou can handle this locking the cache but that creates another performance problem
p4008
aVYou can also fall back to concurrency methods in your language (eg Java 5 concurrency APIs)
p4009
aVIf it's an update (or updates take place that need to be reflected in your read cache) then it's a little more complicated because it's no good having an old value in the cache and a newer value in the database such that you then provide your pages with an inconsistent view of the data
p4010
aVBut broadly speaking there are four approaches to this:
p4011
aVUpdate the cache and then queue a request to update the relevant store;
p4012
aVWrite through caching: the cache provider may provide a mechanism to persist the update and block the caller until that change is made; and
p4013
aVWrite-behind caching: same as write-through caching but it doesn't block the caller
p4014
aVThe update happens asynchronously and separately; and
p4015
aVPersistence as a Service models: this assumes your caching mechanism supports some kind of observability (ie cache event listeners)
p4016
aVBasically an entirely separate process--unknown to the caller--listens for cache updates and persists them as necessary
p4017
aVWhich of the above methodologies you choose will depend a lot on your requirements, what technologies you're using and a whole host of other factors (eg is clustering and failover support required
p4018
aVIt's hard to be more specific than that and give you guidance on what to do without knowing much more detail about your problem (like whether or not you have a problem)
