VThere are several models for doing this
p4162
aVDual license: this model has the code released under two licenses (or more)
p4163
aVOne will be a commercial license
p4164
aVThe other tends to be a restrictive open source license (most commonly GPL because it's viral)
p4165
aVPersonally I think this is a poor model because you can't really take community contributions (at a source code level) like you can with a project that's purely open source
p4166
aVIt really combines the worst of both worlds;
p4167
aVCommercial Support: this is more common on projects like MySQL, Glassfish and the like
p4168
aVThe idea is that you can use the particular product for free but what you're paying for is support (and typically indemnity)
p4169
aVThe problem with this model is that the number of people willing to take their chances on the unsupported version greatly outweighs those that aren't
p4170
aVLike the previous model you tend to no longer have community development;
p4171
aVCommercial Documentation: this is a variation upon commercial support
p4172
aVThe software is free to use and you have limited documentation
p4173
aVYou can get really good documentation if you're preapred to pay for it
