VThere's a combination of techniques:
p5259
aVFirstly, they need to understand what the application does
p5260
aVSounds trite I know but I've worked in trading applications and it can take people a long time to get their head around what, say, a market maker does because that's built on top of a lot of knowledge about how financial markets operate and what they do
p5261
aVJust a term like "spread" has all sorts of assumed knowledge built into it
p5262
aVThis should be done interactively rather than handing someone a tutorial or a user manual
p5263
aVAlso, and this is really important, the user user should drive
p5264
aVUsing the mouse and keyboard rather than watching is what builds muscle memory and ingrained responses
p5265
aVYou'll get much better retention rates that way
p5266
aVAlso, rather than saying "click here now do this" put them on the spot and ask them "what would you do here"
p5267
aVYou can often get a useful insight into the usability of your application this way since the new person isn't tainted by all the history that you and your existing team has
p5268
aVYou can't teach someone everything but show them enough that they can navigate around the application and do simple tasks
p5269
aVSecondly, give them an architectural overview
p5270
aVIf this takes more than an hour or two you're going into too much detail
p5271
aVThey'll simply forget it
p5272
aVI find it's better to actually give this as a face to face talk rather than handing them an architectural design document (which generally just causes people eyes to glaze over)
p5273
aVLastly, give them small, relatively easy bugs to fix that aren't time critical
p5274
aVThis will get them familiar with the basics of checking out the code, building it, deploying it, running it, etc
p5275
aVIt's important that it's simple because things always go wrong with new code
p5276
aVYou might need the right environment variable set up to properly build the code or whatever
p5277
aVGive them a complex problem and if something goes wrong they'll get lost in figuring out if its environment, if it's because they're doing something wrong and so on
p5278
aVIt also goes without saying that you can't leave them in a corner to figure this out
p5279
aVSomeone eneds to keep an eye on them to make sure they don't get bogged down
p5280
aVThis will also give you a good insight into their personality: what happens when they get stuck
p5281
aVDo they freeze up
p5282
aVDo they ask for help
p5283
aVDo they try and nut it out
p5284
aVDo they give up too easily
p5285
aVAt the same time they're learning about the code
