VWell, imho PHP is a bad example for this because PHP is not object-oriented
p5538
aVYes it has objects
p5539
aVYes they support inheritance and all those OO principles
p5540
aVIt supports objects
p5541
aVThere's a difference
p5542
aVI say this because PHP doesn't by default exist in a state between requests
p5543
aVEvery single HTTP request will completely recreate a PHP environment from scratch (which is reasonably cheap), meaning there is no static data persisted between requests
p5544
aVYou might say "what about session data
p5545
aV(and maybe append an "a ha
p5546
aVbut that isn't persistent data in a PHP sense either
p5547
aVIt's (typically) stored in the filesystem and keyed by a cookie the client sends
p5548
aVWhy do I mention these two things
p5549
aVBecause the "global" scope in not like the global scope in C, Java, C++ or these other languages because they tend to persist between requests
p5550
aVPHP is more like the CGI programming model from the 90s (which is no coincidence because that's where it originated)
p5551
aVSo your objects aren't truly global: they are simply visible to all parts of the code servicing the current request
p5552
aVTo me, that's nowhere near as bad
p5553
aVIn fact, I often find it quite acceptable
p5554
aVSometimes it's every necessary (eg in a callback to preg_replace_callback if you want to send information back to the caller or pass state to the callback without doing eval()/create_function() hacks)
p5555
aVAnd the point about PHP not being object-oriented is because even in PHP 5 OO features are still somewhat "tacked on", meaning you could quite happily code away and code well in PHP without ever using them
p5556
aVThis is different to, say, Java where you have to create a class even if all you do is write a bunch of static methods in it
p5557
aVSo if you want to learn OO, honestly I wouldn't do it in PHP
p5558
aVPHP is good for a lot of things but it's designed to have an HTTP request lifecycle (yes I know you can run it from the command line but that's not what the vast majority of users do) and it's quite good at the job it's designed for
