VThis is touching on two separate issues
p5658
aVFirstly, session hijacking
p5659
aVThis is where a third party discovers, say, an authenticated cookie and gains access to someone else's details
p5660
aVSecondly, there is session data security
p5661
aVBy this I mean that you store data in the cookie (such as the username)
p5662
aVThis is not a good idea
p5663
aVAny such data is fundamentally untrustworthy just like HTML form data is untrustworthy (irrespective of what Javascript validation and/or HTML length restrictions you use, if any) because a client is free to submit what they want
p5664
aVYou'll often find people (rightly) advocating sanitizing HTML form data but cookie data will be blindly accepted on face value
p5665
aVBig mistake
p5666
aVIn fact, I never store any information in the cookie
p5667
aVI view it as a session key and that's all
p5668
aVIf you intend to store data in a cookie I strongly advise you to reconsider
p5669
aVEncryption of this data does not make the information any more trustworth because symmetric encryption is susceptible to brute-force attack
p5670
aVObviously AES-256 is better than, say, DES (heh) but 256-bits of security doesn't necessarily mean as much as you think it does
p5671
aVFor one thing, SALTs are typically generated according to an algorithm or are otherwise susceptible to attack
p5672
aVFor another, cookie data is a prime candidate for crib attacks
p5673
aVIf it is known or suspected that a username is in the encrypted data will hey, there's your crib
p5674
aVThis brings us back to the first point: hijacking
p5675
aVIt should be pointed out that on shared-hosting environments in PHP (as one example) your session data is simply stored on the filesystem and is readable by anyone else on that same host although they don't necessarily know which site it is for
p5676
aVSo never store plaintext passwords, credit card numbers, extensive personal details or anything that might otherwise be deemed as sensitive in session data in such environments without some form of encryption or, better yet, just storing a key in the session and storing the actual sensitive data in a database
p5677
aVNote: the above is not unique to PHP
p5678
aVBut that's server side encryption
p5679
aVNow you could argue that encrypting a session with some extra data will make it more secure from hijacking
p5680
aVA common example is the user's IP address
p5681
aVProblem is many people use the same PC/laptop at many different locations (eg Wifi hotspots, work, home)
p5682
aVAlso many environments will use a variety of IP addresses as the source address, particularly in corporate environments
p5683
aVYou might also use the user agent but that's guessable
p5684
aVSo really, as far as I can tell, there's no real reason to use cookie encryption at all
p5685
aVI never did think there was but in light of this question I went looking to be proven either right or wrong
p5686
aVI found a few threads about people suggesting ways to encrypt cookie data, transparently do it with Apache modules, and so on but these all seemed motivated by protecting data stored in a cookie (which imho you shouldn't do)
p5687
aVI've yet to see a security argument for encrypting a cookie that represents nothing more than a session key
p5688
aVI will happily be proven wrong if someone can point out something to the contrary
