VLet me take a crack at this
p7755
aVFirst of, I've written some on this subject in Using an ORM or plain SQL
p7756
aVSpecifically to address your points:
p7757
aVLearning Curve/Ease of Use
p7758
aVIbatis is about SQL
p7759
aVIf you know SQL the learning curve for ibatis is trivial
p7760
aVIbatis does some things on top of SQL such as:
p7761
aVgroup by;
p7762
aVdiscriminated types; and
p7763
aVdynamic SQL
p7764
aVthat you'll still need to learn but the biggest hurdle is SQL
p7765
aVJPA (which includes Hibernate) on the other hand tries to distance itself from SQL and present things in an object rather than a relational way
p7766
aVAs Joel points out however, abstractions are leaky and JPA is no exception
p7767
aVTo do JPA you'll still need to know about relational models, SQL, performance tuning of queries and so forth
p7768
aVWhereas Ibatis will simply having you apply the SQL you know or are learning, JPA will require you to know something else: how to configure it (either XML or annotations)
p7769
aVBy this I mean figuring out that foreign key relationships are a relationship (one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many) of some kind, the type mapping, etc
p7770
aVIf you know SQL I would say the barrier to learning JPA is actually higher
p7771
aVIf you don't, it's more of a mixed result with JPA allowing you to effectively defer learning SQL for a time (but it doesn't put it off indefinitely)
p7772
aVWith JPA once you setup your entities and their relationships then other developers can simply use them and don't need to learn everything about configuring JPA
p7773
aVThis could be an advantage but a developer will still need to know about entity managers, transaction management, managed vs unmanaged objects and so on
p7774
aVIt's worth noting that JPA also has its own query language (JPA-SQL), which you will need to learn whether or not you know SQL
p7775
aVYou will find situations where JPA-SQL just can't do things that SQL can
p7776
aVProductivity
p7777
aVThis is a hard one to judge
p7778
aVPersonally I think I'm more productive in ibatis but I'm also really comfortable with SQL
p7779
aVSome will argue they're way more productive with Hibernate but this is possibly due--at least in part--to unfamiliarity with SQL
p7780
aVAlso the productivity with JPA is deceptive because you will occasionally come across a problem with your data model or queries that takes you a half a day to a day to solve as you turn up logging and watch what SQL your JPA provider is producing and then working out the combination of settings and calls to get it to produce something that's both correct and performant
p7781
aVYou just don't have this kind of problem with Ibatis because you've written the SQL yourself
p7782
aVYou test it by running the SQL inside PL/SQL Developer, SQL Server Management Studio, Navicat for MySQL or whatever
p7783
aVAfter the query is right, all you're doing is mapping inputs and outputs
p7784
aVAlso I found JPA-QL to be more awkward than pure SQL
p7785
aVYou need separate tools to just run a JPA-QL query to see the results and it's something more you have to learn
p7786
aVI actually found this whole part of JPA rather awkward and unwieldy although some people love it
p7787
aVMaintainability/Stability
p7788
aVThe danger with Ibatis here is proliferation meaning your dev team may just keep adding value objects and queries as they need them rather than looking for reuse whereas JPA has one entitty per table and once you have that entity, that's it
p7789
aVNamed queries tend to go on that entity so are hard to miss
p7790
aVAd-hoc queries can still be repeated but I think it's less of a potential problem
p7791
aVThat comes at the cost of rigidity however
p7792
aVOften in an application you will need bits and pieces of data from different tables
p7793
aVWith SQL it's easy because you can write a single query (or a small number of queries) to get all that data in one hit and put it in a custom value object just for that purpose
p7794
aVWith JPA you are moving up that logic into your business layer
p7795
aVEntities are basically all or nothing
p7796
aVNow that's not strictly true
p7797
aVVarious JPA providers will allow you to partially load entities and so forth but even there you're talking about the same discrete entitites
p7798
aVIf you need data from 4 tables you either need 4 entities or you need to combine the data you want into some kind of custom value object in the business or presentation layer
p7799
aVOne other thing I like about ibatis is that all your SQL is external (in XML files)
p7800
aVSome will cite this is as a disadvantage but not me
p7801
aVYou can then find uses of a table and/or column relatively easy by searching your XML files
p7802
aVWith SQL embedded in code (or where there is no SQL at all) it can be a lot harder to find
p7803
aVYou can also cut and paste SQL into a database tool and run it
p7804
aVI can't overstate enough how many times this has been useful to me over the years
p7805
aVPerformance/Scalability
p7806
aVHere I think ibatis wins hands down
p7807
aVIt's straight SQL and low cost
p7808
aVBy its nature JPA simply won't be able to manage the same level of latency or throughput
p7809
aVNow what JPA has going for it is that latency and throughput are only rarely problems
p7810
aVHigh performance systems however do exist and will tend to disfavour more heavyweight solutions like JPA
p7811
aVPlus with ibatis you can write a query that returns exactly the data you want with the exact columns that you need
p7812
aVFundamentally there's no way JPA can beat (or even match) that when it's returning discrete entities
p7813
aVEase of Troubleshooting
p7814
aVI think this one is a win for Ibatis too
p7815
aVLike I mentioned above, with JPA you will sometimes spend half a day getting a query or entity produce the SQL you want or diagnosing a problem where a transaction fails because the entity manager tried to persist an unmanaged object (which could be part of a batch job where you've committed a lot of work so it might be nontrivial to find)
p7816
aVBoth of them will fail if you try to use a table or column that doesn't exist, which is good
p7817
aVOther criteria
p7818
aVNow you didn't mention portability as one of your requirements (meaning moving between database vendors)
p7819
aVIt's worth noting that here JPA has the advantage
p7820
aVThe annotations are less portable than, say, Hibernate XML (eg standard JPA annotations don't have an equivalent for Hibernate's "native" ID type) but both of them are more portable than ibatis / SQL
p7821
aVAlso I've seen JPA / Hibernate used as a form of portable DDL, meaning you run a small Java program that creates the database schema from JPA configuration
p7822
aVWith ibatis you'll need a script for each supported database
p7823
aVThe downside of portability is that JPA is, in some ways, lowest common denominator, meaning the supported behaviour is largely the common supported behaviour across a wide range of database vendors
p7824
aVIf you want to use Oracle Analytics in ibatis, no problem
p7825
aVIn JPA
p7826
aVWell, that's a problem
