aVAn awful lot of magic goes into making JPA work including load-time weaving (instrumentation) and usually one or more levels of caching
p10715
aVWhat's more the entity manager needs to record changes and handle updates of managed objects
p10716
aVThere is no easy facility that I know of to instruct the entity manager that a given entity should be stored in one table or another
p10717
aVSuch a move operation would implicitly require a delete from one table and insertion into another
p10718
aVIf there are child entities this gets more difficult
p10719
aVNot impossible mind you but it's such an unusual corner case I'm not sure anyone would ever bother
p10720
aVA lower-level SQL/JDBC framework such as Ibatis may be a better bet as it will give you the control that you want
p10721
aVI've also given thought to dynamically changing or assigning at annotations at runtime
p10722
aVWhile I'm not yet sure if that's even possible, even if it is I'm not sure it'd necessarily help
p10723
aVI can't imagine an entity manager or the caching not getting hopelessly confused by that kind of thing happening
p10724
aVThe other possibility I thought of was dynamically creating subclasses at runtime (as anonymous subclasses) but that still has the annotation problem and again I'm not sure how you add that to an existing persistence unit
p10725
aVIt might help if you provided some more detail on what you're doing and why
p10726
aVWhatever it is though, I'm leaning towards thinking you need to rethink what you're doing or how you're doing it or you need to pick a different persistence technology
