VThe main benefit of an external CSS file is that:
p10956
aVIt can be used on multiple pages; and
p10957
aVIt can be cached so it doesn't need to be loaded on every page
p10958
aVSo, if there is potential for reuse of the dynamically generated CSS between pages or on multiple views of the same page then an external file could add value
p10959
aVThere are several common patterns for dynamically generated CSS
p10960
ag2257
aVGenerating a subset for a page
p10961
aVI've seen this occasionally
p10962
aVA developer decides to limit the amount of CSS per page by only sending what's necessary
p10963
aVI don't imagine this is the case for you but I'm mentioning it for completeness
p10964
aVThis is a misguided effort at optimization
p10965
aVIt's cheaper to send the whole lot and just cache it effectively
p10966
ag4699
aVUser-selected theme
p10967
aVIf the user selects a particular look for your site, that's what I'm talking about
p10968
aVThis implies they might select a whole package of CSS and there might be a limited set to choose from
p10969
aVUsually this will be done by having one or more base CSS files and then oen or more theme CSS files
p10970
aVThe best solution here is to send the right combination of external CSS files by dynamically generating the page header with the right  elements and then caching those files effectively
p10971
ag6330
aVUser-rolled theme
p10972
aVThis goes beyond (2) to where the user can select, say, colours, fonts and sizes to the point where you can't package those choices into a single theme bundle but you have to generate a set of CSS for that user
p10973
aVIn this case you will probably still have some common CSS
p10974
aVSend that as an external CSS files (again, caching them effectively)
p10975
aVThe dynamic content may be best on the page or you may still be able to make use of external files because there is no reason a  can't point to a script instead of a static file
p10976
aVFor example:
p10977
aVwhere the query string is generated dynamically by your header from who is logged in
p10978
aVThat script will look up the user preferences and generate a dynamic CSS file
p10979
aVThis can be cached effectively whereas putting it directly in the HTML file can't be (unless the whole HTML file can be cached effectively)
p10980
ag6339
aVRules-based CSS generation
p10981
aVI've written a reporting system before that took a lot of rules specified by either the user or a report writer and a custom report and generated a complete HTML page (based on the tables and/or charts they requested in the custom report definition) and styled them according to the rules
p10982
aVThis truly was dynamic CSS
p10983
aVThing is, there is potential for caching here too
p10984
aVThe HTML page generates a dynamic link like this:
p10985
aVwhere 'annual-sales' is the report ID and 0001 is like a version
p10986
aVWhen the rules change you create a new version and each version for each report can be cached effectively
p10987
aVConclusion
p10988
aVSo I can't say definitively whether external CSS files are appropriate or not to you but having seen and developed for each of the scenarios above I have a hard time believing that you can't get some form of caching out of your CSS at which point it should be external
p10989
aVI've written about the issue of effective CSS in Supercharging CSS in PHP but the principles and techniques apply in any language, not just PHP
p10990
aVYou may also want to refer to the related question Multiple javascript/css files: best practices
