aVYou're saying O(n log(n)) which is in fact worse than O(n)
p13501
aVDo you perhaps mean O(log n)
p13502
aVIf so, the answer is no
p13503
aVYou can't invert a linked list in O(log n)
p13504
aVO(n) is trivial (and the obvious solution)
p13505
aVO(n log(n)) doesn't make a lot of sense
p13506
aVEdit: Ok, so you do mean O(n log(n))
p13507
aVThen the answer is yes
p13508
aVHow
p13509
aVEasy
p13510
aVYou sort the list:
p13511
aVCount the length of the list
p13512
aVCost: O(n);
p13513
aVCreate an array of that same size;
p13514
aVCopy the elements of the linked list into the array in random order, putting the original order as part of the element
p13515
aVFor example: [A,B,C] -> [(B,2),(C,3),(A,1)]
p13516
aVCost: O(n);
p13517
aVSort the array using an efficient sort (eg quick sort) in inverted original order eg [(C,3),(B,2),(A,1)]
p13518
aVCost: O(n log(n));
p13519
aVCreate a linked list from the reversed array
p13520
aVCost: O(n)
p13521
aVTotal Cost: O(n log(n))
p13522
aVDespite all the intermediate steps, the sort is the most expensive operation
p13523
aVThe O(n) other steps are constant (meaning the number of steps is not a factor of n) so the total cost is O(n log(n))
p13524
aVEdit 2: I originally didn't put the list items in random order but realized that you could argue that an efficient sort on an already sorted list was less than O(n log(n)) even if you were reversing it
p13525
aVNow I'm not completely convinced that that's the case but the above revision removes that potential criticism
p13526
aVAnd yes, this is a pathological question (and answer)
p13527
aVOf course you can do it in O(n)
