aVFunctional programming (Haskell, Scheme, Ocaml, Lisp, others) tend to espouse "pure" functions
p13990
aVA pure function is one with no side effects
p13991
aVMany imperative languages (eg Java, C#) also encourage the use of immutable objects (an immutable object is one whose state cannot change once created)
p13992
aVThe reason for (or at least the effect of) both of these things is largely the same: they make multithreaded code much easier
p13993
aVA pure function by definition is threadsafe
p13994
aVAn immutable object by definition is threadsafe
p13995
aVThe advantage processes have is that there is less shared state (generally)
p13996
aVIn traditional UNIX C programming, doing a fork() to create a new process would result in shared process state and this was used as a means of IPC (inter-process communication) but generally that state is replaced (with exec()) with something else
p13997
aVBut threads are much cheaper to create and destroy and they take less system resources (in fact, the operating itself may have no concept of threads yet you can still create multithreaded programs)
p13998
aVThese are called green threads
