aVI will say that with bespoke software development, you have a few common models:
p15693
aVClient contract developer to write something where the client assumes all the risk but owns the IP
p15694
aVThe developer will get paid either fixed price or T&M; (time and materials);
p15695
aVDeveloper retains IP
p15696
aVThis should lower the cost to the client as the assumption is the developer can sell the software elsewhere to recover costs;
p15697
aVDeveloper creates something on his own and then sees whether he can sell it
p15698
aVThis is generally only done when you anticipate being able to sell a lot of software
p15699
aVHopefully this will be cheaper again to the client even though the developer has assumed far more risk
p15700
aVTo put it another way:
p15701
aVThe software is worth something
p15702
aVBy definition, ownership is worth something;
p15703
aVRisk is the other big factor
p15704
aVWho is assuming the risk in this relationship
p15705
aVIf you're getting paid regardless, the client is;
p15706
aVWhat potential market is there for this software
p15707
aVThe bigger the market, the more the software is worth;
p15708
aVThe more you get paid upfront, the less risk you are assuming
