p16791
aVThe whole point of finding an authorization scheme is to define one that is as fine or coarse grained as you need to balance flexibility and administration/development
p16792
aVTwo common schemes that may be of interest to you:
p16793
aVGive each user a type in the database
p16794
aVWhen they log in put that type (eg User, Admin, Moderator) in the session and check that on each relevant page;
p16795
aVGive each user one or more roles (so someone could, say, be both an Admin and a Moderator or just one of them or neither)
p16796
aVThis requires a separate table (users and userroles) and putting probably an array in the session to indicate roles but is more flexible than (1)
p16797
aVRole-based authorization is very common
p16798
aVThere are many, many variations upon these two and just as many alternatives
p16799
aVVarious schemes can be combined
p16800
aVThis is why generic authorization libraries for me fall short because they have contrary needs of being broad enough to cover a large number of use cases and being coarse-grained enough to be useful for the individual user
