p16915
aVGaussian distributions understate the risk of massive drops in price (called the "fat tail" phenomenon)
p16916
aVBack in the 60s, Mandelbrot (yes the fractal guy) showed that cotton price movements fit a Levy distribution
p16917
aVTake a look at:
p16918
aVMonte Carlo simulated stock price time series and random number generator;
p16919
aVThe Generation of Random Variables Having a Levy-Stable Distribution;
p16920
aVThe GNU maths library has a method for creating a Levy alpha stable distribution;
p16921
aVAnother thing to consider is that over time, the adjusted (for splits and so forth) price of stocks tends to go up
p16922
aVIn statistics terms this is called Heterodasticity, which tends to be undesirable from a modelling point of view
p16923
aVThis is factored out typically in two ways:
p16924
aVInstead of generating a random series of prices, you generate a random series of price changes (deltas); and
