VJust like developers, QA have (or should have) minimum standards to adhere to
p17757
aVWhen raising an issue they need to provide:
p17758
aVa repeatable test case;
p17759
aVa screenshot; or
p17760
aVa description of the problem and any pattern if it is inconsistent or other not reproducible
p17761
aVIf I have to go over to QA and ask what the problem is or how they produced it, I get annoyed
p17762
aV"This doesn't work" just isn't good enough
p17763
aVIn one system I developed (a Web reporting system) I generated all the input data on each generated report
p17764
aVWhen QA ran a report and noticed a problem they could go to a blind URL and download a ZIP file that contained:
p17765
aVthe definition of the report;
p17766
aVthe template used; and
p17767
aVany database input
p17768
aVOn the dev side I wrote a tool that could rerun the report based solely on that ZIP file
p17769
aVThis had several effects:
p17770
aVIf QA raised an issue, I could say "wheres the ZIP file
p17771
ag2539
aVOnce they got into the habit, it became far easier to raise an issue; and
p17772
aVProblems were trivial to reproduce and retest by developers
p17773
aVThe effect was profound and I think that highlights one key issue: developers don't like it when things are hard to test, hard to reproduce and so on
p17774
aVLikewise, QA people don't like anything that makes their job harder and they like anything that makes it easier
p17775
aVSo my advice for working harmoniously with QA comes down to:
p17776
aVuse an issue-tracking system
p17777
aVThis is absolute #1 priority
p17778
aVEverything needs an audit trail;
p17779
aVhave someone in charge of QA that is responsible for the team
p17780
aVThey can address issues of insufficient detail provided in QA-raised issues
p17781
aVRather than going to each tester, go to this person and let them deal with it as they see fit
p17782
aVFor one thing this should lead to consistent standards;
p17783
aVprovide as many tools and diagnostics as possible to QA to make their life easier
p17784
aVIt'll make your life easier too;
p17785
aVdon't judge developers or QA on pass rates
p17786
aVDon't even produce such statistics
p17787
aVThey lead to an adversarial rather than collaborative environment
p17788
aVYou are (or should be) all on the same team;
p17789
aVhave weekly defect meetings between QA, development and project management to discuss latest, resolved and outstanding issues at a more macro-level
p17790
aVThis can be useful for both a project tracking point of view as well as generally getting a feel of any major issues or problem areas you may have
