VUltimately I would look at it this way: a DSL (like any programming language) is a set of lexical tokens and idioms that you can use to explain how to do something
p18526
aVImplicit within that set of tokens is a set of idioms
p18527
aVThe idea of any language is that you select an appropriate one that makes it easier to express expected algorithms
p18528
aVA good example are reporting languages (eg Natural)
p18529
aVThat's because reports have common idioms like groups, breaking conditions and so on
p18530
aVAnyone who has done that in a general purpose language would tell you that it can be really tedious to do things like break conditions but it's certainly possible
p18531
aVSo the question you should be asking is this: are there any common idioms that would be tedious, difficult or extremely verbose to express in a general purpose language
p18532
aVYou should also be asking: is there a particular subset of functionality that you are most interested in that would benefit by making it a language concept
p18533
aVThis could be things like vectors and matrices for linear algebra (with the appropriate operations) or the same for integral/differnetial calculus or differential equations
p18534
aVWhat you'd really like to have in the end with a DSL is where, say, a 500 line program could be express as 50-100 lines of your DSL and this applies for most "expected" algorithms
p18535
aVI guess it's a little like normalization in data modelling where the goal is to remove repeating groups
p18536
aVWriting the same 10-20 lines of code with a little variation suggests a common idiom
p18537
aVAs for a library of functions, that is a more limited view of the same thing (ultimately) except that a library of function is merely a package of different behaviours
p18538
aVThat ssumes you define a library of functions as just that and don't instead include complex object hierarchies, closures and so on
p18539
aVIf you do then the line between a "library of functions" and a DSL is blurred
p18540
aVI would think of a library of functions as, say, the set of math functions that exist in most modern languages (sin, cos, square root and so forth)
p18541
aVSo I guess it comes down to:
p18542
aVPackages of code -> library of functions
p18543
aVCommon idioms -> DSL
