aVThe term you're looking for (in ANSI SQL terms) is "isolation level"
p19525
aVMany databases will default to an isolation level where reads on uncommitted data will block
p19526
aVSo if transaction A updates record 1234 in table T and then transaction B tries to select record 1234 before A commits or rolls back then B will block until A does one of those things
p19527
aVSee MySQL Transactions, Part II - Transaction Isolation Levels
p19528
aVOne serious downside of this is that batch update operations that live in long-running transactions (typically) can potentially block many requests
p19529
aVYou can also set it so B will see uncommitted data but that is often ill-advised
p19530
aVAlternatively you can use a scheme called MVCC ("Multiversion concurrency control"), which will give different transactions a consistent view of the data based on the time the transaction started
p19531
aVThis avoids the uncommitted read problem (reading data that may be rolled back) and is much more scalable, especially in the context of long-lived transactions
p19532
aVMySQL supports MVCC
