VQuick note, this is almost certainly confusing Big O notation (which is an upper bound) with Theta notation (which is a two-side bound)
p21099
aVIn my experience this is actually typical of discussions in non-academic settings
p21100
aVApologies for any confusion caused
p21101
aVThe simplest definition I can give for Big-O notation is this:
p21102
aVBig-O notation is a relative representation of the complexity of an algorithm
p21103
aVThere are some important and deliberately chosen words in that sentence:
p21104
aVrelative: you can only compare apples to apples
p21105
aVYou can't compare an algorithm to do arithmetic multiplication to an algorithm that sorts a list of integers
p21106
aVBut a comparison of two algorithms to do arithmetic operations (one multiplication, one addition) will tell you something meaningful;
p21107
aVrepresentation: Big-O (in its simplest form) reduces the comparison between algorithms to a single variable
p21108
aVThat variable is chosen based on observations or assumptions
p21109
aVFor example, sorting algorithms are typically compared based on comparison operations (comparing two nodes to determine their relative ordering)
p21110
aVThis assumes that comparison is expensive
p21111
aVBut what if comparison is cheap but swapping is expensive
p21112
aVIt changes the comparison; and
p21113
aVcomplexity: if it takes me one second to sort 10,000 elements how long will it take me to sort one million
p21114
aVComplexity in this instance is a relative measure to something else
p21115
aVCome back and reread the above when you've read the rest
p21116
aVThe best example of Big-O I can think of is doing arithmetic
p21117
aVTake two numbers (123456 and 789012)
p21118
aVThe basic arithmetic operations we learnt in school were:
p21119
aVaddition;
p21120
aVsubtraction;
p21121
aVmultiplication; and
p21122
aVdivision
p21123
aVEach of these is an operation or a problem
p21124
aVA method of solving these is called an algorithm
p21125
aVAddition is the simplest
p21126
aVYou line the numbers up (to the right) and add the digits in a column writing the last number of that addition in the result
p21127
aVThe 'tens' part of that number is carried over to the next column
p21128
aVLet's assume that the addition of these numbers is the most expensive operation in this algorithm
p21129
aVIt stands to reason that to add these two numbers together we have to add together 6 digits (and possibly carry a 7th)
p21130
aVIf we add two 100 digit numbers together we have to do 100 additions
p21131
aVIf we add two 10,000 digit numbers we have to do 10,000 additions
p21132
aVSee the pattern
p21133
aVThe complexity (being the number of operations) is directly proportional to the number of digits n in the larger number
p21134
aVWe call this O(n) or linear complexity
p21135
aVSubtraction is similar (except you may need to borrow instead of carry)
p21136
aVMultiplication is different
p21137
aVYou line the numbers up, take the first digit in the bottom number and multiply it in turn against each digit in the top number and so on through each digit
p21138
aVSo to multiply our two 6 digit numbers we must do 36 multiplications
p21139
aVWe may need to do as many as 10 or 11 column adds to get the end result too
p21140
aVIf we have two 100-digit numbers we need to do 10,000 multiplications and 200 adds
p21141
aVFor two one million digit numbers we need to do one trillion (1012) multiplications and two million adds
p21142
aVAs the algorithm scales with n-squared, this is O(n2) or quadratic complexity
p21143
aVThis is a good time to introduce another important concept:
p21144
aVWe only care about the most significant portion of complexity
p21145
aVThe astute may have realized that we could express the number of operations as: n2 + 2n
p21146
aVBut as you saw from our example with two numbers of a million digits apiece, the second term (2n) becomes insignificant (accounting for 0
p21147
aV0002% of the total operations by that stage)
p21148
aVOne can notice that we've assumed the worst case scenario here
p21149
aVWhile multiplying 6 digit numbers if one of them is 4 digit and the other one is 6 digit, then we only have 24 multiplications
p21150
aVStill we calculate the worst case scenario for that 'n', i
p21151
aVe when both are 6 digit numbers
p21152
aVHence Big-O notation is about the Worst-case scenario of an algorithm
p21153
aVThe Telephone Book
p21154
aVThe next best example I can think of is the telephone book, normally called the White Pages or similar but it'll vary from country to country
p21155
aVBut I'm talking about the one that lists people by surname and then initials or first name, possibly address and then telephone numbers
p21156
aVNow if you were instructing a computer to look up the phone number for "John Smith" in a telephone book that contains 1,000,000 names, what would you do
p21157
aVIgnoring the fact that you could guess how far in the S's started (let's assume you can't), what would you do
p21158
aVA typical implementation might be to open up to the middle, take the 500,000th and compare it to "Smith"
p21159
aVIf it happens to be "Smith, John", we just got real lucky
p21160
aVFar more likely is that "John Smith" will be before or after that name
p21161
aVIf it's after we then divide the last half of the phone book in half and repeat
p21162
aVIf it's before then we divide the first half of the phone book in half and repeat
p21163
aVAnd so on
p21164
aVThis is called a binary search and is used every day in programming whether you realize it or not
p21165
aVSo if you want to find a name in a phone book of a million names you can actually find any name by doing this at most 20 times
p21166
aVIn comparing search algorithms we decide that this comparison is our 'n'
p21167
aVFor a phone book of 3 names it takes 2 comparisons (at most)
p21168
aVFor 7 it takes at most 3
p21169
aVFor 15 it takes 4
p21170
aV\u2026
p21171
aVFor 1,000,000 it takes 20
p21172
aVThat is staggeringly good isn't it
p21173
aVIn Big-O terms this is O(log n) or logarithmic complexity
p21174
aVNow the logarithm in question could be ln (base e), log10, log2 or some other base
p21175
aVIt doesn't matter it's still O(log n) just like O(2n2) and O(100n2) are still both O(n2)
p21176
aVIt's worthwhile at this point to explain that Big O can be used to determine three cases with an algorithm:
p21177
aVBest Case: In the telephone book search, the best case is that we find the name in one comparison
p21178
aVThis is O(1) or constant complexity;
p21179
aVExpected Case: As discussed above this is O(log n); and
p21180
aVWorst Case: This is also O(log n)
p21181
aVNormally we don't care about the best case
p21182
aVWe're interested in the expected and worst case
p21183
aVSometimes one or the other of these will be more important
p21184
aVBack to the telephone book
p21185
aVWhat if you have a phone number and want to find a name
p21186
aVThe police have a reverse phone book but such look-ups are denied to the general public
p21187
aVOr are they
p21188
aVTechnically you can reverse look-up a number in an ordinary phone book
p21189
aVHow
p21190
aVYou start at the first name and compare the number
p21191
aVIf it's a match, great, if not, you move on to the next
p21192
aVYou have to do it this way because the phone book is unordered (by phone number anyway)
p21193
aVSo to find a name given the phone number (reverse lookup):
p21194
aVBest Case: O(1);
p21195
aVExpected Case: O(n) (for 500,000); and
p21196
aVWorst Case: O(n) (for 1,000,000)
p21197
aVThe Travelling Salesman
p21198
aVThis is quite a famous problem in computer science and deserves a mention
p21199
aVIn this problem you have N towns
p21200
aVEach of those towns is linked to 1 or more other towns by a road of a certain distance
p21201
aVThe Travelling Salesman problem is to find the shortest tour that visits every town
p21202
aVSounds simple
p21203
aVThink again
p21204
aVIf you have 3 towns A, B and C with roads between all pairs then you could go:
p21205
aVA \u2192 B \u2192 C
p21206
aVA \u2192 C \u2192 B
p21207
aVB \u2192 C \u2192 A
p21208
aVB \u2192 A \u2192 C
p21209
aVC \u2192 A \u2192 B
p21210
aVC \u2192 B \u2192 A
p21211
aVWell actually there's less than that because some of these are equivalent (A \u2192 B \u2192 C and C \u2192 B \u2192 A are equivalent, for example, because they use the same roads, just in reverse)
p21212
aVIn actuality there are 3 possibilities
p21213
aVTake this to 4 towns and you have (iirc) 12 possibilities
p21214
aVWith 5 it's 60
p21215
aV6 becomes 360
p21216
aVThis is a function of a mathematical operation called a factorial
p21217
aVBasically:
p21218
ag3255
aV= 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 120
p21219
ag18560
aV= 6 × 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 720
p21220
ag16639
aV= 7 × 6 × 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 5040
p21221
aV\u2026
p21222
aV25
p21223
aV= 25 × 24 × \u2026 × 2 × 1 = 15,511,210,043,330,985,984,000,000
p21224
aV\u2026
p21225
aV50
p21226
aV= 50 × 49 × \u2026 × 2 × 1 = 3
p21227
aV04140932 × 1064
p21228
aVSo the Big-O of the Travelling Salesman problem is O(n
p21229
aVor factorial or combinatorial complexity
p21230
aVBy the time you get to 200 towns there isn't enough time left in the universe to solve the problem with traditional computers
p21231
aVSomething to think about
p21232
aVPolynomial Time
p21233
aVAnother point I wanted to make quick mention of is that any algorithm that has a complexity of O(na) is said to have polynomial complexity or is solvable in polynomial time
p21234
aVO(n), O(n2) etc are all polynomial time
p21235
aVSome problems cannot be solved in polynomial time
p21236
aVCertain things are used in the world because of this
p21237
aVPublic Key Cryptography is a prime example
p21238
aVIt is computationally hard to find two prime factors of a very large number
p21239
aVIf it wasn't, we couldn't use the public key systems we use
p21240
aVAnyway, that's it for my (hopefully plain English) explanation of Big O (revised)
