VShort answer
p21297
aVSometimes
p21298
aVTechnically every abstraction has a cost and a programming language is an abstraction for how the CPU works
p21299
aVC however is very close
p21300
aVYears ago I remember laughing out loud when I logged onto my UNIX account and got the following fortune message (when such things were popular):
p21301
aVThe C Programming Language -- A
p21302
aVlanguage which combines the
p21303
aVflexibility of assembly language with
p21304
aVthe power of assembly language
p21305
aVIt's funny because it's true: C is like portable assembly language
p21306
aVIt's worth noting that assembly language just runs however you write it
p21307
aVThere is however a compiler in between C and the assembly language it generates and that is extremely important because how fast your C code is has an awful lot to do with how good your compiler is
p21308
aVWhen gcc came on the scene one of the things that made it so popular was that it was often so much better than the C compilers that shipped with many commercial UNIX flavours
p21309
aVNot only was it ANSI C (none of this K&R; C rubbish), was more robust and typically produced better (faster) code
p21310
aVNot always but often
p21311
aVI tell you all this because there is no blanket rule about the speed of C and assembler because there is no objective standard for C
p21312
aVLikewise, assembler varies a lot depending on what processor you're running, your system spec, what instruction set you're using and so on
p21313
aVHistorically there have been two CPU architecture families: CISC and RISC
p21314
aVThe biggest player in CISC was and still is the Intel x86 architecture (and instruction set)
p21315
aVRISC dominated the UNIX world (MIPS6000, Alpha, Sparc and so on)
p21316
aVCISC won the battle for the hearts and minds
p21317
aVAnyway, the popular wisdom when I was a younger developer was that hand-written x86 could often be much faster than C because the way the architecture worked, it had a complexity that benefitted from a human doing it
p21318
aVRISC on the other hand seemed designed for compilers so noone (I knew) wrote say Sparc assembler
p21319
aVI'm sure such people existed but no doubt they've both gone insane and been institutionalized by now
p21320
aVInstruction sets are an important point even in the same family of processors
p21321
aVCertain Intel processors have extensions like SSE through SSE4
p21322
aVAMD had their own SIMD instructions
p21323
aVThe benefit of a programming language like C was someone could write their library so it was optimized for whichever processor you were running on
p21324
aVThat was hard work in assembler
p21325
aVThere are still optimizations you can make in assembler that no compiler could make and a well written assembler algoirthm will be as fast or faster than it's C equivalent
p21326
aVThe bigger question is: is it worth it
p21327
aVUltimately though assembler was a product of its time and was more popular at a time when CPU cycles were expensive
p21328
aVNowadays a CPU that costs $5-10 to manufacture (Intel Atom) can do pretty much anything anyone could want
p21329
aVThe only real reason to write assembler these days is for low level things like some parts of an operating system (even so the vast majority of the Linux kernel is written in C), device drivers, possibly embedded devices (although C tends to dominate there too) and so on
p21330
aVOr just for kicks (which is somewhat masochistic)
