aVIn general a HashMap works like this: it has a variable number of what are commonly called "buckets"
p22639
aVThe number of buckets can change over time (as entries are added and removed) but it is always a power of 2
p22640
aVLet's say a given  has 16 buckets
p22641
aVWhen you call put() to add an entry, the hashCode() of the key is calculated and then a mask is taken depending on the size of the buckets
p22642
aVIf you (bitwise) AND the hashCode() with 15 (0x0F) you will get the last 4 bits, equaling a number between 0 and 15 inclusive:
p22643
aVNow if there is already an entry in that bucket you have what's called a collision
p22644
aVThere are multiple ways of dealing with this but the one used by HashMap (and is probably the most common overall) is bucketing
p22645
aVAll the entries with the same masked hashCode are put in a list of some kind
p22646
aVSo to find if a given key is in the map already:
p22647
aVCalculate the masked hash code;
p22648
aVFind the appropriate bucket;
p22649
aVIf it's empty, key not found;
p22650
aVIf is isn't empty, loop through all entries in the bucket checking equals()
p22651
aVLooking through a bucket is a linear (O(n)) operation but it's on a small subset
p22652
aVThe hashcode bucket determination is essentially constant (O(1))
p22653
aVIf buckets are sufficiently small then access to a HashMap is usually described as "near O(1)"
p22654
aVYou can make a couple of observations about this
p22655
aVFirstly, if you have a bunch of objects that all return 42 as their hash code a  will still work but it will operate as an expensive list
p22656
aVAccess will be O(n) (as everything will be in the same bucket regardless of the number of buckets)
