VWell the brute force method goes something like this:
p23093
aVFor n rows there are 2n subsets
p23094
aVFor n columns there are 2n subsets
p23095
aVFor an n x n matrix there are 22n subsets
p23096
aV0 elements is a valid subset but obviously if you have 0 rows or 0 columns the total is 0 so there are really 22n-2+1 subsets but that's no different
p23097
aVSo you can work out each combination by brute force as an O(an) algorithm
p23098
aVFast
p23099
aV:)
p23100
aVIt would be quicker to work out what the maximum possible value is and you do that by adding up all the positive numbers in the grid
p23101
aVIf those numbers happen to form a valid sub-matrix (meaning you can create that set by removing rows and/or columns) then there's your answer
p23102
aVImplicit in this is that if none of the numbers are negative then the complete matrix is, by definition, the answer
p23103
aVAlso, knowing what the highest possible maximum is possibly allows you to shortcut the brute force evaluation since if you get any combination equal to that maximum then that is your answer and you can stop checking
p23104
aVAlso if all the numbers are non-positive, the answer is the maximum value as you can reduce the matrix to a 1 x 1 matrix with that 1 value in it, by definition
p23105
aVHere's an idea: construct 2n-1 n x m matrices where 1 <= m <= n
p23106
aVProcess them one after the other
p23107
aVFor each n x m matrix you can calculate:
p23108
aVThe highest possible maximum sum (as per above); and
p23109
aVWhether no numbers are positive allowing you to shortcut the answer
p23110
aVif (1) is below the currently calculate highest maximum sum then you can discard this n x m matrix
p23111
aVIf (2) is true then you just need a simple comparison to the current highest maximum sum
p23112
aVThis is generally referred to as a pruning technique
p23113
aVWhat's more you can start by saying that the highest number in the n x n matrix is the starting highest maximum sum since obviously it can be a 1 x 1 matrix
p23114
aVI'm sure you could tweak this into a (slightly more) efficient recursive tree-based search algorithm with the above tests effectively allowing you to eliminate (hopefully many) unnecessary searches
