VWell the first thing you have to realize is the OOAD ("Object-oriented analysis and design") is a tool and not a means to an end
p23909
aVWhat you get out of that process is a model, not a true representation of what you're modelling
p23910
aVThat model makes certain assumptions
p23911
aVThe purpose of that model is to solve a problem you have
p23912
aVSo how do you know how to design objects
p23913
aVHow do you know if you've done it right
p23914
aVBy the end result: has it solved your problem
p23915
aVSo, for the Car example, in some models a car count could simply be an integer count, for example the car traffic through an intersection in a traffic model
p23916
aVIn such a model rarely do you care about the make, model or construction of cars, just the number
p23917
aVYou might care about the type of vehicle to the point of is it a truck or car (for example)
p23918
aVDo you model that as a Vehicle object with a type of Car or Truck
p23919
aVOr just separate carCount and truckCount tallies
p23920
aVThe short answer is: whichever works best
p23921
aVThe normal test for something being an object or not is does it have behaviour
p23922
aVRemember that ultimately objects = data + behaviour
p23923
aVSo you might say that cars have the following state:
p23924
aV# of wheels;
p23925
aVHeight of suspension;
p23926
aVLeft or right drive;
p23927
aVColour;
p23928
aVWidth;
p23929
aVWeight;
p23930
aVLength;
p23931
aVHeight;
p23932
aV# of doors;
p23933
aVWhether it has a sunroof;
p23934
aVWhether it has a stereo, CD player, MP3 player and/or satnav;
p23935
aVSize of the petrol tank;
p23936
aVNumber of cylinders;
p23937
aV# of turbo charges and/or fuel injection;
p23938
aVMaximum torque;
p23939
aVMaximum brake-horsepower;
p23940
aVand so on
p23941
aVChances are you'll only care about a small subset of that: pick whatever is relevant
