p24691
aVIf you read through this I've determined that the only way to store a complete game state is by storing a complete list of moves
p24692
aVRead on for why
p24693
aVSo I use a slightly simplified version of the problem for piece layout
p24694
aVThe Problem
p24695
aVThis image illustrates the starting Chess position
p24696
aVChess occurs on an 8x8 board with each player starting with an identical set of 16 pieces consisting of 8 pawns, 2 rooks, 2 knights, 2 bishops, 1 queen and 1 king as illustrated here:
p24697
aVPositions are generally recorded as a letter for the column followed by the number for the row so White\u2019s queen is at d1
p24698
aVMoves are most often stored in algebraic notation, which is unambiguous and generally only specifies the minimal information necessary
p24699
aVConsider this opening:
p24700
aVe4 e5
p24701
aVNf3 Nc6
p24702
aV\u2026
p24703
aVwhich translates to:
p24704
aVWhite moves king\u2019s pawn from e2 to e4 (it is the only piece that can get to e4 hence \u201ce4\u201d);
p24705
aVBlack moves the king\u2019s pawn from e7 to e5;
p24706
aVWhite moves the knight (N) to f3;
p24707
aVBlack moves the knight to c6
p24708
aVThe board looks like this:
p24709
aVAn important ability for any programmer is to be able to correctly and unambiguously specify the problem
p24710
aVSo what\u2019s missing or ambiguous
p24711
aVA lot as it turns out
p24712
aVBoard State vs Game State
p24713
aVThe first thing you need to determine is whether you\u2019re storing the state of a game or the position of pieces on the board
p24714
aVEncoding simply the positions of the pieces is one thing but the problem says \u201call subsequent legal moves\u201d
p24715
aVThe problem also says nothing about knowing the moves up to this point
p24716
aVThat\u2019s actually a problem as I\u2019ll explain
p24717
aVCastling
p24718
aVThe game has proceeded as follows:
p24719
aVe4 e5
p24720
aVNf3 Nc6
p24721
aVBb5 a6
p24722
aVBa4 Bc5
p24723
aVThe board looks as follows:
p24724
aVWhite has the option of castling
p24725
aVPart of the requirements for this are that the king and the relevant rook can never have moved, so whether the king or either rook of each side has moved will need to be stored
p24726
aVObviously if they aren\u2019t on their starting positions, they have moved otherwise it needs to be specified
p24727
aVThere are several strategies that can be used for dealing with this problem
p24728
aVFirstly, we could store an extra 6 bits of information (1 for each rook and knight position) to indicate whether that piece had moved
p24729
aVWe could streamline this by only storing a bit for one of these six squares if the right piece happens to be in it
p24730
aVAlternatively we could treat each unmoved piece as another piece type so instead of 6 piece types on each side (pawn, rook, knight, bishop, queen and king) there are 8 (adding unmoved rook and unmoved king)
p24731
aVEn Passant
p24732
aVAnother peculiar and often-neglected rule in Chess is En Passant
p24733
aVThe game has progressed
p24734
aVe4 e5
p24735
aVNf3 Nc6
p24736
aVBb5 a6
p24737
aVBa4 Bc5
p24738
aVO-O b5
p24739
aVBb3 b4
p24740
aVc4
p24741
aVBlack\u2019s pawn on b4 now has the option of moving his pawn on b4 to c3 taking the White pawn on c4
p24742
aVThis only happens on the first opportunity meaning if Black passes on the option now he can\u2019t take it next move
p24743
aVSo we need to store this
p24744
aVIf we know the previous move we can definitely answer if En Passant is possible
p24745
aVAlternatively we can store whether each pawn on its 4th rank has just moved there with a double move forward
p24746
aVOr we can look at each possible En Passant position on the board and have a flag to indicate whether its possible or not
p24747
aVPromotion
p24748
aVIt is White\u2019s move
p24749
aVIf White moves his pawn on h7 to h8 it can be promoted to any other piece (but not the king)
p24750
aV99% of the time it is promoted to a Queen but sometimes it isn\u2019t, typically because that may force a stalemate when otherwise you\u2019d win
p24751
aVThis is written as:
p24752
aVThis is important in our problem because it means we can\u2019t count on there being a fixed number of pieces on each side
p24753
aVIt is entirely possible (but incredibly unlikely) for one side to end up with 9 queens, 10 rooks, 10 bishops or 10 knights if all 8 pawns get promoted
p24754
aVStalemate
p24755
aVWhen in a position from which you cannot win your best tactic is to try for a stalemate
p24756
aVThe most likely variant is where you cannot make a legal move (usually because any move when put your king in check)
p24757
aVIn this case you can claim a draw
p24758
aVThis one is easy to cater for
p24759
aVThe second variant is by threefold repetition
p24760
aVIf the same board position occurs three times in a game (or will occur a third time on the next move), a draw can be claimed
p24761
aVThe positions need not occur in any particular order (meaning it doesn\u2019t have to the same sequence of moves repeated three times)
p24762
aVThis one greatly complicates the problem because you have to remember every previous board position
p24763
aVIf this is a requirement of the problem the only possible solution to the problem is to store every previous move
p24764
aVLastly, there is the fifty move rule
p24765
aVA player can claim a draw if no pawn has moved and no piece has been taken in the previous fifty consecutive moves so we would need to store how many moves since a pawn was moved or a piece taken (the latest of the two
p24766
aVThis requires 6 bits (0-63)
p24767
aVWhose Turn Is It
p24768
aVOf course we also need to know whose turn it is and this is a single bit of information
p24769
aVTwo Problems
p24770
aVBecause of the stalemate case, the only feasible or sensible way to store the game state is to store all the moves that led to this position
p24771
aVI\u2019ll tackle that one problem
p24772
aVThe board state problem will be simplified to this: store the current position of all pieces on the board ignoring castling, en passant, stalemate conditions and whose turn it is
p24773
aVPiece layout can be broadly handled in one of two ways: by storing the contents of each square or by storing the position of each piece
p24774
aVSimple Contents
p24775
aVThere are six piece types (pawn, rook, knight, bishop, queen and king)
p24776
aVEach piece can be White or Black so a square may contain one of 12 possible pieces or it may be empty so there are 13 possibilities
p24777
aV13 can be stored in 4 bits (0-15) So the simplest solution is to store 4 bits for each square times 64 squares or 256 bits of information
p24778
aVThe advantage of this method is that manipulation is incredibly easy and fast
p24779
aVThis could even be extended by adding 3 more possibilities without increasing the storage requirements: a pawn that has moved 2 spaces on the last turn, a king that hasn\u2019t moved and a rook that hasn\u2019t moved, which will cater for a lot of previously mentioned issues
p24780
aVBut we can do better
p24781
aVBase 13 Encoding
p24782
aVIt is often helpful to think of the board position as a very large number
p24783
aVThis is often done in computer science
p24784
aVFor example, the halting problem treats a computer program (rightly) as a large number
p24785
aVThe first solution treats the position as a 64 digit base 16 number but as demonstrated there is redundancy in this information (being the 3 unused possibilities per \u201cdigit\u201d) so we can reduce the number space to 64 base 13 digits
p24786
aVOf course this can\u2019t be done as efficiently as base 16 can but it will save on storage requirements (and minimizing storage space is our goal)
p24787
aVIn base 10 the number 234 is equivalent to 2 x 102 + 3 x 101 + 4 x 100
p24788
aVIn base 16 the number 0xA50 is equivalent to 10 x 162 + 5 x 161 + 0 x 160 = 2640 (decimal)
p24789
aVSo we can encode our position as p0 x 1363 + p1 x 1362 +
p24790
aV+ p63 x 130 where pi represents the contents of square i
p24791
aV2256 equals approximately 1
p24792
aV16e77
p24793
aV1364 equals approximately 1
p24794
aV96e71, which requires 237 bits of storage space
p24795
aVThat saving of a mere 7
p24796
aV5% comes at a cost of significantly increased manipulation costs
