aVVariable Width Alphabets
p24804
aVThe previous two methods can both be described as fixed-width alphabetic encoding
p24805
aVEach of the 11, 13 or 16 members of the alphabet is substituted for another value
p24806
aVEach \u201ccharacter\u201d is the same width but the efficiency can be improved when you consider that each character is not equally likely
p24807
aVConsider Morse code (pictured above)
p24808
aVCharacters in a message are encoded as a sequence of dashes and dots
p24809
aVThose dashes and dots are transferred over radio (typically) with a pause between them to delimit them
p24810
aVNotice how the letter E (the most common letter in English) is a single dot, the shortest possible sequence, whereas Z (the least frequent) is two dashes and two beeps
p24811
aVSuch a scheme can significantly reduce the size of an expected message but comes at the cost of increasing the size of a random character sequence
p24812
aVIt should be noted that Morse code has another inbuilt feature: dashes are as long as three dots so the above code is created with this in mind to minimize the use of dashes
p24813
aVSince 1s and 0s (our building blocks) don\u2019t have this problem, it\u2019s not a feature we need to replicate
p24814
aVLastly, there are two kinds of rests in Morse code
p24815
aVA short rest (the length of a dot) is used to distinguish between dots and dashes
p24816
aVA longer gap (the length of a dash) is used to delimit characters
p24817
aVSo how does this apply to our problem
