aVHuffman Coding
p24819
aVThere is an algorithm for dealing with variable length codes called Huffman coding
p24820
aVHuffman coding creates a variable length code substitution, typically uses expected frequency of the symbols to assign shorter values to the more common symbols
p24821
aVIn the above tree, the letter E is encoded as 000 (or left-left-left) and S is 1011
p24822
aVIt should be clear that this encoding scheme is unambiguous
p24823
aVThis is an important distinction from Morse code
p24824
aVMorse code has the character separator so it can do otherwise ambiguous substitution (eg 4 dots can be H or 2 Is) but we only have 1s and 0s so we choose an unambiguous substitution instead
