aVPiece Position
p24836
aVAs mentioned, another way of attacking this problem is to instead store the position of each piece a player has
p24837
aVThis works particularly well with endgame positions where most squares will be empty (but in the Huffman coding approach empty squares only use 1 bit anyway)
p24838
aVEach side will have a king and 0-15 other pieces
p24839
aVBecause of promotion the exact make up of those pieces can vary enough that you can\u2019t assume the numbers based on the starting positions are maxima
p24840
aVThe logical way to divide this up is store a Position consisting of two Sides (White and Black)
p24841
aVEach Side has:
p24842
aVA king: 6 bits for the location;
p24843
aVHas pawns: 1 (yes), 0 (no);
p24844
aVIf yes, number of pawns: 3 bits (0-7+1 = 1-8);
p24845
aVIf yes, the location of each pawn is encoded: 45 bits (see below);
p24846
aVNumber of non-pawns: 4 bits (0-15);
p24847
aVFor each piece: type (2 bits for queen, rook, knight, bishop) and location (6 bits)
p24848
aVAs for the pawn location, the pawns can only be on 48 possible squares (not 64 like the others)
p24849
aVAs such, it is better not to waste the extra 16 values that using 6 bits per pawn would use
p24850
aVSo if you have 8 pawns there are 488 possibilities, equalling 28,179,280,429,056
p24851
aVYou need 45 bits to encode that many values
p24852
aVThat\u2019s 105 bits per side or 210 bits total
p24853
aVThe starting position is the worst case for this method however and it will get substantially better as you remove pieces
p24854
aVIt should be pointed out that there are less than 488 possibilities because the pawns can\u2019t all be in the same square  The first has 48 possibilities, the second 47 and so on
p24855
aV48 x 47 x \u2026 x 41 = 1
p24856
aV52e13 = 44 bits storage
p24857
aVYou can further improve this by eliminating the squares that are occupied by other pieces (including the other side) so you could first place the white non-pawns then the black non-pawns, then the white pawns and lastly the black pawns
