VMy advice on data modeling is:
p25129
aVYou should favour optional (nullable) columns over 1:1 joins generally speaking
p25130
aVThere are still instances where 1:1 makes sense, usually revolving around subtyping
p25131
aVPeople tend to be more squeamish when it comes to nullable columns than they do about joins oddly;
p25132
aVDon't make a model too indirect unless really justified (more on this below);
p25133
aVFavour joins over aggregation
p25134
aVThis can vary so it needs to be tested
p25135
aVSee Oracle vs MySQL vs SQL Server: Aggregation vs Joins for an example of this;
p25136
aVJoins are better than N+1 selects
p25137
aVAn N+1 select is, for example, selecting an order from a database table and then issuing a separate query to get all the line items for that order;
p25138
aVThe scalability of joins is usually only an issue when you're doing mass selects
p25139
aVIf you select a single row and then join that to a few things rarely is this a problem (but sometimes it is);
p25140
aVForeign keys should always be indexed unless you're dealing with a trivially small table;
p25141
aVMore in Database Development Mistakes Made by AppDevelopers
p25142
aVNow as for directness of a model, let me give you an example
p25143
aVLet's say you're designing a system for authentication and authorization of users
p25144
aVAn overengineered solution might look something like this:
p25145
aVAlias (id, username, user_id);
p25146
aVUser (id,
p25147
ag2539
aVEmail (id, user_id, email address);
p25148
aVLogin (id, user_id,
p25149
aVLogin Roles (id, login_id, role_id);
p25150
aVRole (id, name);
p25151
aVRole Privilege (id, role_id, privilege_id);
p25152
aVPrivilege (id, name)
p25153
aVSo you need 6 joins to get from the username entered to the actual privileges
p25154
aVSure there might be an actual requirement for this but more often than not this kind of system is put in because of the hand-wringing by some developer thinking they might someday need it even though every user only has one alias, user to login is 1:1 and so on
p25155
aVA simpler solution is:
p25156
aVUser (id, username, email address, user type)
p25157
aVand, well, that's it
p25158
aVPerhaps if you need a complex role system but it's also quite possible that you don't and if you do it's reasonably easy to slot in (user type becomes a foreign key into a user types or roles table) or it's generally straightforward to map the old to the new
p25159
aVThis is thing about complexity: it's easy to add and hard to remove
p25160
aVUsually it's a constant vigil against unintended complexity, which is bad enough without going and making it worse by adding unnecessary complexity
