VWhat really is scaling
p27598
aVScaling is the increasing in capacity and/or usage of your application
p27599
aVWhat do developers do to make their application scalable
p27600
aVEither allow their applications to scale vertically or horizontally
p27601
aVHorizontal scaling is about doing things in parallel
p27602
aVVertical scaling is about doing things faster
p27603
aVThis typically means more powerful hardware
p27604
aVOften when people talk about horizontal scalability the ideal is to have (near-)linear scalability
p27605
aVThis means that if one $5k production box can handle 2,000 concurrent users then adding 4 more should handle 10,000 concurrent users
p27606
aVThe closer it is to that figure the better
p27607
aVThe ideal for highly scalable apps is to have near-limitless near-linear horizontal scalability such that you can just plug in another box and your capacity increases by an expected amount with little or no diminishing returns
p27608
aVIdeally redundancy is part of the equation too but that's typically a separate issue
p27609
aVThe poster child for this kind of scalability is, of course, Google
p27610
aVWhat are the factors that are looked after by developers during scaling
p27611
aVHow much scale should be planned for
p27612
aVThere's no point spending time and money on a problem you'll never have;
p27613
aVIs it possible and/or economical to scale vertically
p27614
aVThis is the preferred option as it is typically much, much cheaper (in the short term);
p27615
aVIs it worth the (often significant) cost to enable your application to scale horizontally
p27616
aVDistributed/multithreaded apps are significantly more difficult and expensive to write
p27617
aVAny tips and tricks about scaling web applications
p27618
aVYes:
p27619
aVDon't worry about problems you'll never have;
p27620
aVDon't worry much about problems you're unlikely to have
p27621
aVChances are things will have changed long before you have them;
p27622
aVDon't be afraid to throw away code and start again
p27623
aVHaving automated tests makes this far easier; and
p27624
aVThink in terms of developer time being expensive
p27625
aV(4) is a key point
p27626
aVYou might have a poorly written app that will require $20,000 of hardware to essentially fix
p27627
aVNowadays $20,000 buys a lot of power (64+GB of RAM, 4 quad core CPUs, etc), probably more than 99% of people will ever need
p27628
aVIs it cheaper just to do that or spend 6 months rewriting and debugging a new app to make it faster
p27629
aVIt's easily the first option
p27630
aVSo I'll add another item to my list: be pragmatic
