VTranslating one language to another is just a special case for the class of programs called compilers, interpreters and translators
p28584
aVThis class of program will take a stream of input symbols ("source code") that can usually be described by a formal grammar and will output a stream of symbols
p28585
aVThat output stream of symbols can be:
p28586
aVNative assembly code, usually for the operating system and hardware the machine is running on
p28587
aVIf so, the program is referred to as a compiler;
p28588
aVNative assembly code for a different OS and/or hardware
p28589
aVThis can be called a compiler too but is often referred to as a cross-compiler;
p28590
aVTo an intermediate form that can be executed by a virtual machine of some kind
p28591
aVThis isn't a true compiler but is often called a compiler anyway
p28592
aVThe Java, C#, F#, VB
p28593
aVNET, etc "compilers" all fall into this category;
p28594
aVTo another language entirely
p28595
aVThis is called a translator and there are examples of, say, Java to C# translators
p28596
aVThey typically have varying degrees of success because idioms often aren't readily translatable;
p28597
aVInterpreters follow the same principle but typically execute the processed form in-place rather than saving it somewhere
p28598
aVPerl, PHP and shell scripts all fall into this category
p28599
aVPHP for example will store opcodes in an opcode cache as an intermediate form (if opcoding caching is enabled) but this intermediate form isn't stored so it's still safe to call PHP an interpreter
