VThe definitions of encoding and decoding are somewhat subjective
p34104
aVBoth are forms of transliteration, being the process of converting from one alphabet to another
p34105
aVASCII to UTF8, ASCII to base64, etc are all examples of this
p34106
aVWhat distinguishes the two is that "encoding" is often used when transliterating from a usable format to a transmission or intermediate format of some kind and decoding is the reverse
p34107
aVThis is where the "subjective" bit comes in
p34108
aVASCII to UTF8 can be viewed as encoding or decoding depending on the context
p34109
aVOther formats like base64 are used almost universally for transmission only (eg binary data in email) and as such converting to them is almost universally called "encoding" and converting from as "decoding"
p34110
aVThe important point to take away from all this is that something like ASCII or UTF8 is not magical in any way
p34111
aVAll these formats are simply an agreed-upon encoding of information into a binary format
p34112
aVSo ASCII 65 is 'A' for no other reason than that's the standard
p34113
aVUnicode formats get more interesting because they make the distinction between the code point and the encoding
p34114
aVUnicode defines the code points for each character
p34115
aVThe binary data is different for each encoding format
p34116
aVFor example, see Unicode Character 'EURO-CURRENCY SIGN' (U+20A0) to see all the different binary values for one code point
