VThe answer to this question depends on exactly what you want to learn
p36206
aVPython and Ruby
p36207
aVHigh level languages like Python and Ruby are often suggested because they are high level and the syntax is quite readable
p36208
aVHowever these languages all have abstractions for the common data structures
p36209
aVThere's nothing stopping you implementing your own versions as a learning exercise but you may find that you're building high level data structures on top of other high level data structures, which isn't necessarily useful
p36210
aVAlso, Ruby and Python are dynamically typed languages
p36211
aVThis can be good but it can also be confusing for the beginner and it can be harder (initially) to catch errors since they typically won't be apparent until runtime
p36212
ag13554
aVC is at the other extreme
p36213
aVIt's good if you want to learn really low-level details like how the memory is managed but memory management is suddenly an important consideration, as in correct usage of malloc()/free()
p36214
aVThat can be distracting
p36215
aVAlso, C isn't object-oriented
p36216
aVThat's not a bad thing but simply worth noting
p36217
aVC++
p36218
aVC++ has been mentioned
p36219
aVAs I said in the comment, I think this is a terrible choice
p36220
aVC++ is hideously complicated even in simple usage and has a ridiculous amount of "gotchas"
p36221
aVAlso, C++ has no common base class
p36222
aVThis is important because data structures like hash tables rely on there being a common base class
p36223
aVYou could implement a version for a nominal base class but it's a little less useful
p36224
aVJava
p36225
aVJava has also been mentioned
p36226
aVMany people like to hate Java and it's true that the language is extremely verbose and lacking in some of the more modern language features (eg closures) but none of that really matters
p36227
aVJava is statically typed and has garbage collection
p36228
aVThis means the Java compiler will catch many errors that dynamically typed languages won't (until runtime) and there's no dealing with segmentation faults (which isn't to say you can't leak memory in Java; obviously you can)
p36229
aVI think Java is a fine choice
p36230
aVC#
p36231
aVC# the language is like a more modern version of Java
p36232
aVLike Java it is a managed (garbage collected) intermediate compiled language that runs on a virtual machine
p36233
aVEvery other language listed here apart form C/C++ also run on a virtual machine but Python, Ruby, etc are interpreted directly rather than compiled to bytecode
p36234
aVC# has the same pros and cons as Java, basically
p36235
aVHaskell (etc)
