VCheck every element against every other element
p38984
aVThe naive solution is to check every element against every other element
p38985
aVThis is wasteful and yields an O(n2) solution, even if you only go "forward"
p38986
aVSort then remove duplicates
p38987
aVA better solution is sort the array and then check each element to the one next to it to find duplicates
p38988
aVChoose an efficient sort and this is O(n log n)
p38989
aVThe disadvantage with the sort-based solution is order is not maintained
p38990
aVAn extra step can take care of this however
p38991
aVPut all entries (in the unique sorted array) into a hashtable, which has O(1) access
p38992
aVThen iterate over the original array
p38993
aVFor each element, check if it is in the hash table
p38994
aVIf it is, add it to the result and delete it from the hash table
p38995
aVYou will end up with a resultant array that has the order of the original with each element being in the same position as its first occurrence
p38996
aVLinear sorts of integers
p38997
aVIf you're dealing with integers of some fixed range you can do even better by using a radix sort
p38998
aVIf you assume the numbers are all in the range of 0 to 1,000,000 for example, you can allocate a bit vector of some 1,000,001
p38999
aVFor each element in the original array, you set the corresponding bit based on its value (eg a value of 13 results in setting the 14th bit)
p39000
aVThen traverse the original array, check if it is in the bit vector
p39001
aVIf it is, add it to the result array and clear that bit from the bit vector
p39002
aVThis is O(n) and trades space for time
p39003
aVHash table solution
p39004
aVWhich leads us to the best solution of all: the sort is actually a distraction, though useful
p39005
aVCreate a hashtable with O(1) access
p39006
aVTraverse the original list
p39007
aVIf it is not in the hashtable already, add it to the result array and add it to the hash table
p39008
aVIf it is in the hash table, ignore it
p39009
aVThis is by far the best solution
p39010
aVSo why the rest
p39011
aVBecause problems like this are about adapting knowledge you have (or should have) to problems and refining them based on the assumptions you make into a solution
p39012
aVEvolving a solution and understanding the thinking behind it is far more useful than regurgitating a solution
p39013
aVAlso, hash tables are not always available
p39014
aVTake an embedded system or something where space is VERY limited
p39015
aVYou can implement an quick sort in a handful of opcodes, far fewer than any hash table could be
