VThe key to solving this problem is first making an observation: the center of the largest circle that will fit inside an arbitrary polygon is the point that is:
p39476
aVInside the polygon; and
p39477
aVFurthest from any point on the edges of the polygon
p39478
aVWhy
p39479
aVBecause every point on the edge of a circle is equidistant from that center
p39480
aVBy definition, the largest circle will have the largest radius and will touch the polygon on at least two points so if you find the point inside furthest from the polygon you've found the center of the circle
p39481
aVThis problem appears in geography and is solved iteratively to any arbitrary precision
p39482
aVIts called the Poles of Inaccessibility problem
p39483
aVSee Poles of Inaccessibility: A Calculation Algorithm for the Remotest Places on Earth
p39484
aVThe basic algorithm works like this:
p39485
aVDefine R as a rectilinear region from (xmin,ymin) to (xmax,ymax);
p39486
aVDivide R into an arbitrary number of points
p39487
aVThe paper uses 21 as a heuristic (meaning divide the height and width by 20);
p39488
aVClip and points that are outside the polygon;
p39489
aVFor the remainder find the point that is furthest from any point on the edge;
p39490
aVFrom the point define a new R with smaller intervals and bounds and repeat from step 2 to get to any arbitrary precision answer
p39491
aVThe paper reduces R by a factor of the square root of 2
p39492
aVOne note: testing if a point is inside the polygon or not
p39493
aVThe simplest solution to this part of the problem is to cast a ray to the right of the point
p39494
aVIf it crosses an odd number of edges, it's within the polygon
p39495
aVIf it's an even number, it's outside
p39496
aVAlso, as far as testing the distance to any edge there are two cases you need to consider:
p39497
aVThe point is perpendicular to a point on that edge (within the bounds of the two vertices); or
p39498
aVIt isn't
p39499
aV(2) is easy
p39500
aVThe distance to the edge is the minimum of the distances to the two vertices
p39501
aVFor (1), the closest point on that edge will be the point that intersects the edge at a 90 degree angle starting from the point you're testing
p39502
aVSee Distance of a Point to a Ray or Segment
